which allows you to combine the simplicity of Markdown with the flexibility of
React.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;css-1bkk5q4&quot;&gt;For example, I can have editable code snippets that accept updates from the user, like this:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;css-1bkk5q4&quot;&gt;Update &lt;code class=&quot;css-0&quot;&gt;Change this text&lt;/code&gt;, click the button, and you can see the text you just
put in!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;css-1bkk5q4&quot;&gt;I&amp;#x27;m using &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.gatsbyjs.org/starters/lekoarts/gatsby-starter-minimal-blog/&quot; class=&quot;css-1od09yo&quot;&gt;this starter&lt;/a&gt;, which helped to get everything set up.
The website is hosted on Github Pages, and builds and deploys automatically on
every new commit using Travis CI, so I can just write and commit! Everything is
open source at &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/kylebarron/kylebarron.github.io&quot; class=&quot;css-1od09yo&quot;&gt;https://github.com/kylebarron/kylebarron.github.io&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</content:encoded></item></channel></rss>